1
00:00:11,583 --> 00:00:12,833
Hey!

2
00:00:13,791 --> 00:00:15,832
[Detective Agnes] <i>What compelled you
to break into the home</i>

3
00:00:15,833 --> 00:00:17,250
<i>- of a decorated detective?</i>
- Hey!

4
00:00:19,375 --> 00:00:21,124
- What were you after?
- The Road.

5
00:00:21,125 --> 00:00:23,707
- What road?
- You, of all people, should know.

6
00:00:23,708 --> 00:00:26,541
[chanting in Latin]

7
00:00:30,416 --> 00:00:32,874
[Agatha in English] <i>If you've got
the goods to break a spell</i>

8
00:00:32,875 --> 00:00:35,415
<i>cast by the Scarlet Witch,</i>

9
00:00:35,416 --> 00:00:37,040
why do you need The Road?

10
00:00:37,041 --> 00:00:38,583
Again, who are you?

11
00:00:39,416 --> 00:00:40,624
I'm...

12
00:00:40,625 --> 00:00:42,499
Someone's put a sigil on that boy.

13
00:00:42,500 --> 00:00:45,790
A sigil is a redaction spell
that hides something.

14
00:00:45,791 --> 00:00:47,082
Did you put the sigil on me?

15
00:00:47,083 --> 00:00:50,790
Actually, I wouldn't know.
It works on the witch who cast it as well.

16
00:00:50,791 --> 00:00:54,082
Sigils are destroyed
when they're no longer needed.

17
00:00:54,083 --> 00:00:56,207
- [Teen] How old were you?
- Thirteen, maybe.

18
00:00:56,208 --> 00:00:57,708
A lot happened to me at 13, too.

19
00:00:59,833 --> 00:01:01,207
Wake up. Alice. Please wake up.

20
00:01:01,208 --> 00:01:02,707
Don't touch her!

21
00:01:02,708 --> 00:01:05,208
You're so much like your mother.

22
00:01:08,125 --> 00:01:10,541
Wait, what are you...
[grunts and exclaims]

23
00:01:11,875 --> 00:01:13,708
[all screaming]

24
00:01:15,541 --> 00:01:16,708
[Jen] Teen! Help.

25
00:01:18,708 --> 00:01:19,791
- No! No!
- [Lilia yells] No!

26
00:01:48,375 --> 00:01:50,041
[Teen praying in Hebrew]

27
00:01:52,625 --> 00:01:57,083
[people pray along]

28
00:01:59,208 --> 00:02:01,458
[Teen continues praying]

29
00:02:42,458 --> 00:02:48,833
[reading in Hebrew]

30
00:02:51,583 --> 00:02:53,583
[♪ dance music palying]

31
00:03:10,416 --> 00:03:12,207
[Jeff] You look like you're having fun.

32
00:03:12,208 --> 00:03:13,750
Who, me? Never.

33
00:03:14,333 --> 00:03:17,458
Here. Have you eaten anything?
Oh, good. Perfect.

34
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:20,250
- [Rebecca] Oh, look at you.
- [Jeff] Eat this.

35
00:03:21,875 --> 00:03:23,333
We are so proud of you.

36
00:03:26,166 --> 00:03:29,875
We love you more than we could ever hope
to communicate in human words.

37
00:03:31,583 --> 00:03:34,082
- Gross.
- Ew, you're gross.

38
00:03:34,083 --> 00:03:36,125
- You're both disgusting.
- [chuckles]

39
00:03:36,833 --> 00:03:40,166
Thank you for everything.

40
00:03:42,250 --> 00:03:44,499
- William, come on. It's time.
- There you are.

41
00:03:44,500 --> 00:03:46,874
- Yes! Yes! Yes, yes, yes!
- There you go.

42
00:03:46,875 --> 00:03:48,500
[♪ "Hava Nagila" playing]

43
00:03:49,500 --> 00:03:51,708
[boy] Yeah, William!

44
00:03:53,750 --> 00:03:56,666
This is so extra! Okay. Okay.

45
00:04:02,875 --> 00:04:03,875
[♪ dance music playing]

46
00:04:21,208 --> 00:04:22,750
[Voice] Welcome to the curious.

47
00:04:25,875 --> 00:04:27,875
Are we looking behind us, or ahead?

48
00:04:28,541 --> 00:04:29,541
Ahead.

49
00:04:31,833 --> 00:04:32,833
I think.

50
00:04:34,625 --> 00:04:36,291
Yeah, do ahead.

51
00:04:37,416 --> 00:04:39,750
Let us see what the future has in store.

52
00:04:40,333 --> 00:04:42,958
Please. May I have your right palm?

53
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:48,041
Don't tell me everything.

54
00:04:48,625 --> 00:04:50,583
I don't wanna know too much.

55
00:04:52,333 --> 00:04:53,333
Sorry. I...

56
00:04:55,083 --> 00:04:56,416
Just pretend I'm not here.

57
00:05:00,083 --> 00:05:02,125
It's clear that
a long journey lies ahead of you.

58
00:05:03,250 --> 00:05:05,458
This journey will be
one of great transformation and...

59
00:05:06,916 --> 00:05:08,625
[electricity crackling]

60
00:05:13,291 --> 00:05:14,750
Your lifeline is broken in two.

61
00:05:15,500 --> 00:05:16,541
[Teen] What?

62
00:05:17,666 --> 00:05:18,916
That can't be good.

63
00:05:22,500 --> 00:05:23,750
It can mean many things.

64
00:05:24,583 --> 00:05:28,583
It often represents personal growth
and important life changes.

65
00:05:30,041 --> 00:05:31,041
You're becoming a man.

66
00:05:32,791 --> 00:05:33,791
A new you.

67
00:05:37,750 --> 00:05:38,750
I wouldn't worry.

68
00:05:42,083 --> 00:05:43,250
The Tower Reversed.

69
00:05:46,208 --> 00:05:48,500
I thought you were reading my palm.

70
00:05:50,875 --> 00:05:51,875
I'm sorry. I...

71
00:05:53,500 --> 00:05:55,125
I just remembered something, I think.

72
00:05:59,833 --> 00:06:01,625
Okay, well, I probably should...

73
00:06:02,833 --> 00:06:03,833
go back to the party.

74
00:06:06,041 --> 00:06:09,000
Love the vibe in here, though.
It's very early Argento.

75
00:06:10,791 --> 00:06:13,375
You don't need to be a psychic
to see that you're a good egg.

76
00:06:14,166 --> 00:06:15,958
Enjoy the now, baby.

77
00:06:17,208 --> 00:06:18,791
It's the only thing that's certain.

78
00:06:53,833 --> 00:06:56,333
- [♪ dance music playing in distance]
- [people chattering indistinctly]

79
00:07:08,166 --> 00:07:12,833
Oh, sorry.
Um, some kid left this in my tent.

80
00:07:13,750 --> 00:07:15,665
Will you make sure that they get it back?

81
00:07:15,666 --> 00:07:17,666
- Which kid?
- I don't remember.

82
00:07:29,166 --> 00:07:31,415
- [mic tapping]
- [Jeff] <i>Sorry to interrupt.</i>

83
00:07:31,416 --> 00:07:33,457
<i>We've been informed
there's something happening</i>

84
00:07:33,458 --> 00:07:35,624
<i>with the anomaly in Westview.</i>

85
00:07:35,625 --> 00:07:39,750
<i>Everybody needs to go home
as quickly and as safely as possible.</i>

86
00:07:41,041 --> 00:07:42,249
- [all clamoring]
- What's going on?

87
00:07:42,250 --> 00:07:44,665
Sweetheart, I'm so sorry.
I think we have to go.

88
00:07:44,666 --> 00:07:45,749
- Yeah.
- What?

89
00:07:45,750 --> 00:07:48,875
- [people clamoring]
- [sirens wailing]

90
00:07:55,291 --> 00:07:56,957
[Vision] <i>My wife and her flying saucers.</i>

91
00:07:56,958 --> 00:07:59,707
[Wanda] <i>My husband
and his indestructible head.</i>

92
00:07:59,708 --> 00:08:00,957
[audience laughs on radio]

93
00:08:00,958 --> 00:08:02,583
[Rebecca shushes] It's okay.

94
00:08:03,375 --> 00:08:04,875
It's okay. We'll be home soon.

95
00:08:23,958 --> 00:08:25,040
[Jeff] Is it going away?

96
00:08:25,041 --> 00:08:26,707
[Rebecca] It looks like
it's getting smaller.

97
00:08:26,708 --> 00:08:27,916
Mom, look out!

98
00:08:53,666 --> 00:08:58,541
Oh, my God. Oh, my God. Are you okay?
Oh, my God. William. William? William!

99
00:08:59,458 --> 00:09:00,957
- [Rebecca] Is he okay?
- No, he's bleeding.

100
00:09:00,958 --> 00:09:03,040
What? William, can you hear me, baby?

101
00:09:03,041 --> 00:09:04,290
- Call 911.
- I'm trying.

102
00:09:04,291 --> 00:09:06,540
I don't think he's breathing.
I can't get to him.

103
00:09:06,541 --> 00:09:08,165
- [Jeff] It's not going through.
- William.

104
00:09:08,166 --> 00:09:09,625
Oh, no. Jeff. Look.

105
00:09:10,375 --> 00:09:11,790
I'm gonna flag them down.

106
00:09:11,791 --> 00:09:15,458
- William, oh, no! No, no, no!
- [Jeff] Help! Hey!

107
00:09:16,708 --> 00:09:17,833
I'm coming. Hold on.

108
00:09:18,416 --> 00:09:23,958
[in distance] William! Oh, no,
I can't get to him.

109
00:09:33,375 --> 00:09:36,333
- [Billy] <i>Good night, Tommy.</i>
- [Tommy] <i>Good night, Billy.</i>

110
00:09:39,083 --> 00:09:40,875
[gasps] Tommy!

111
00:09:45,083 --> 00:09:46,874
Hey, hey.

112
00:09:46,875 --> 00:09:49,791
- [Jeff] Rebecca.
- [Rebecca] You're all right.

113
00:09:50,291 --> 00:09:51,624
You're gonna be okay.

114
00:09:51,625 --> 00:09:53,040
- Are you okay?
- Is he breathing?

115
00:09:53,041 --> 00:09:54,124
- Yes, he is now.
- Okay.

116
00:09:54,125 --> 00:09:55,624
- [Jeff] Thank God.
- Don't move him.

117
00:09:55,625 --> 00:09:57,083
The ambulance is on the way.

118
00:09:57,791 --> 00:09:59,041
[paramedic] Can you say your name?

119
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:01,125
Do you know where you are?

120
00:10:02,625 --> 00:10:04,166
Do you remember what happened?

121
00:10:04,875 --> 00:10:05,875
It'll be okay.

122
00:10:07,416 --> 00:10:08,416
It's okay.

123
00:10:12,833 --> 00:10:14,707
[Teen breathing heavily]

124
00:10:14,708 --> 00:10:15,958
[Jeff] It's okay.

125
00:10:34,541 --> 00:10:37,540
- [Jeff] There's nothing physically wrong?
- [Rebecca] He's clearly different.

126
00:10:37,541 --> 00:10:40,540
[doctor] I'm referring you
to an excellent psychologist.

127
00:10:40,541 --> 00:10:42,583
And of course I'm here, too,
if you need it.

128
00:10:43,208 --> 00:10:44,208
[Rebecca] Thank you.

129
00:10:45,625 --> 00:10:47,208
- [Jeff] Hey, buddy.
- Hey.

130
00:10:50,416 --> 00:10:53,000
This is where you'd say,
"Since when do you call me 'buddy'?"

131
00:10:53,666 --> 00:10:54,833
Would I?

132
00:10:55,416 --> 00:10:57,332
[Rebecca] <i>Seriously?
He's gonna make fun of him?</i>

133
00:10:57,333 --> 00:10:59,500
[Jeff] <i>She's giving me that look.
I'm doing my best here.</i>

134
00:11:02,083 --> 00:11:04,375
It's fine. Just please don't fight.

135
00:11:06,166 --> 00:11:07,791
- What do you mean?
- We're not fighting.

136
00:11:10,208 --> 00:11:12,666
Everything's okay. We're with you.

137
00:11:14,541 --> 00:11:16,250
Yeah, sorry.

138
00:11:19,875 --> 00:11:23,040
So, the doctor was saying
all the scans look clean.

139
00:11:23,041 --> 00:11:24,875
And there's no signs of permanent damage.

140
00:11:25,375 --> 00:11:31,415
She thinks the amnesia will just take
a little time to resolve on its own.

141
00:11:31,416 --> 00:11:32,500
That's all.

142
00:11:33,208 --> 00:11:35,457
[Jeff] The really good news
is you're cleared to be discharged

143
00:11:35,458 --> 00:11:36,541
as soon as tomorrow.

144
00:11:39,000 --> 00:11:41,791
[Rebecca] Well, only if you're ready.
Are you?

145
00:11:43,375 --> 00:11:44,458
Ready?

146
00:11:47,791 --> 00:11:48,916
Yeah, of course.

147
00:12:01,000 --> 00:12:04,124
[Rebecca] Okay. Home sweet, messy,

148
00:12:04,125 --> 00:12:07,291
someday-we're-gonna-get-
that-bathroom-renovated, home.

149
00:12:08,500 --> 00:12:11,708
[Jeff] So happy you're finally home,
William. Goodness.

150
00:12:12,625 --> 00:12:13,625
Thanks.

151
00:12:18,750 --> 00:12:20,624
[Rebecca] Okay.
I'm gonna change the water in this.

152
00:12:20,625 --> 00:12:23,041
[Jeff] I'm gonna pop up the AC.
It's just stuffy.

153
00:12:29,500 --> 00:12:31,125
- Here. Let me get this one.
- Oh, yeah.

154
00:12:33,416 --> 00:12:34,540
[barking]

155
00:12:34,541 --> 00:12:35,750
[Jeff and Rebecca] Greg!

156
00:12:36,750 --> 00:12:39,790
Greg, chill out.
It's William. It's just William.

157
00:12:39,791 --> 00:12:44,791
It's probably just the smell
from the hospital or something.

158
00:12:46,083 --> 00:12:48,083
Okay, come here. Come here. Come here.

159
00:12:51,958 --> 00:12:53,375
[Rebecca] <i>He looks so scared.</i>

160
00:12:54,375 --> 00:12:56,958
[Jeff] <i>Oh, my God. This is so hard.
When will he remember?</i>

161
00:12:59,875 --> 00:13:01,457
I don't understand what's happening.

162
00:13:01,458 --> 00:13:02,625
What? What is it, honey?

163
00:13:03,500 --> 00:13:04,749
[Jeff] <i>The doctor said no stress</i>

164
00:13:04,750 --> 00:13:06,915
<i>but it really feels
like we're stressing him out.</i>

165
00:13:06,916 --> 00:13:08,457
[Rebecca] <i>What are we supposed to do?</i>

166
00:13:08,458 --> 00:13:10,832
<i>How do we fix this? I just want him back!</i>

167
00:13:10,833 --> 00:13:14,666
Please just stop. Please stop!
Please just stop.

168
00:13:15,166 --> 00:13:16,458
Stop what, buddy?

169
00:13:17,166 --> 00:13:18,957
[Rebecca] <i>Maybe seeing
his room will jog some...</i>

170
00:13:18,958 --> 00:13:20,457
[Jeff] <i>What if he never remembers?</i>

171
00:13:20,458 --> 00:13:22,582
<i>What if he just stays like this?</i>

172
00:13:22,583 --> 00:13:24,915
- [Rebecca] <i>His favorite restaurant.
- Lost, anxious, alone?</i>

173
00:13:24,916 --> 00:13:27,082
<i>- There has to be something.
- What if...</i>

174
00:13:27,083 --> 00:13:28,707
<i>- Give me my son!
- Will he be okay?</i>

175
00:13:28,708 --> 00:13:29,875
Stop worrying!

176
00:13:36,708 --> 00:13:37,916
I'm sorry. I just...

177
00:13:43,208 --> 00:13:44,791
Maybe you're right, Mom.

178
00:13:47,750 --> 00:13:49,458
Maybe I just need to see my room.

179
00:13:50,500 --> 00:13:52,375
- How did...
- [Teen] Do you mind if I...

180
00:13:54,375 --> 00:13:55,540
go up alone?

181
00:13:55,541 --> 00:13:57,375
It's no problem. Of course.

182
00:14:05,916 --> 00:14:09,791
Maybe when I come back down,
we can have dinner.

183
00:14:11,541 --> 00:14:12,625
My treat.

184
00:14:13,375 --> 00:14:14,416
[Jeff chuckles]

185
00:15:21,625 --> 00:15:22,750
My name is William Kaplan.

186
00:15:27,875 --> 00:15:28,875
I'm William Kaplan.

187
00:15:31,791 --> 00:15:33,041
I am William Kaplan.

188
00:15:52,583 --> 00:15:53,582
[Teen] I had fun.

189
00:15:53,583 --> 00:15:55,041
And I always have fun with you.

190
00:15:58,541 --> 00:16:00,749
What is this thing?
You always have it with you.

191
00:16:00,750 --> 00:16:01,833
[Teen] It's nothing.

192
00:16:02,625 --> 00:16:04,625
It's a sigil. At least, I...

193
00:16:05,916 --> 00:16:08,915
I think it is.
It's like a puzzle. Sort of.

194
00:16:08,916 --> 00:16:10,333
Puzzle?

195
00:16:12,458 --> 00:16:13,541
Well, have you solved it?

196
00:16:14,125 --> 00:16:15,333
No, it's...

197
00:16:16,625 --> 00:16:17,625
It's impossible.

198
00:16:32,500 --> 00:16:33,916
[Eddie] <i>I'm just gonna say it.</i>

199
00:16:34,750 --> 00:16:35,958
<i>I can't not say it.</i>

200
00:16:36,791 --> 00:16:38,958
<i>I'm just gonna say,
"William Kaplan. I love you."</i>

201
00:16:39,875 --> 00:16:40,875
I...

202
00:16:41,666 --> 00:16:43,916
[chuckles nervously] Sorry. I just...

203
00:16:47,333 --> 00:16:51,082
- I need to tell you something.
- Really? I need to tell you something.

204
00:16:51,083 --> 00:16:53,125
- Yeah, me first.
- Okay.

205
00:16:57,750 --> 00:17:03,540
So this thing happens
when I'm with someone I care a lot about

206
00:17:03,541 --> 00:17:07,916
and they're having intense feelings.

207
00:17:11,625 --> 00:17:14,625
- I already sound like a freak...
- I'm... I'm into it.

208
00:17:17,083 --> 00:17:18,125
The car accident.

209
00:17:20,166 --> 00:17:21,625
I never told you about it, but, uh...

210
00:17:24,375 --> 00:17:25,375
Eddie, I...

211
00:17:26,833 --> 00:17:27,916
I died that night.

212
00:17:29,916 --> 00:17:31,916
And when I came back, I was different.

213
00:17:32,916 --> 00:17:35,500
Something else. Something more.

214
00:17:38,208 --> 00:17:41,625
I'm not William Kaplan.
At least not entirely.

215
00:17:42,958 --> 00:17:45,291
I still don't remember anything
from before the accident.

216
00:17:46,083 --> 00:17:48,666
I just pretended to recover
so my parents wouldn't worry.

217
00:17:50,583 --> 00:17:52,833
But nothing in my life has felt normal
until I met you.

218
00:17:54,958 --> 00:17:57,875
But I want you to know the truth.
I want you to know the real me.

219
00:17:59,083 --> 00:18:00,125
Whoever that is, because...

220
00:18:02,708 --> 00:18:03,708
Because I love you, too.

221
00:18:06,458 --> 00:18:09,041
You love me... too?

222
00:18:10,333 --> 00:18:12,541
- I love you, period.
- [chuckles]

223
00:18:14,500 --> 00:18:15,500
For the first time.

224
00:18:17,000 --> 00:18:18,208
What did you wanna...

225
00:18:22,791 --> 00:18:24,457
So you don't think I'm crazy?

226
00:18:24,458 --> 00:18:27,916
Uh, no, I totally do.
But for completely different reasons.

227
00:18:29,666 --> 00:18:31,416
You're under no obligation
to be this cool.

228
00:18:33,250 --> 00:18:35,999
I do have one question.

229
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:37,415
Just one?

230
00:18:37,416 --> 00:18:39,833
If you're not William Kaplan,

231
00:18:42,583 --> 00:18:43,583
who are you?

232
00:18:47,458 --> 00:18:50,583
- [Teen] So I've compiled a dossier.
- Of course you have.

233
00:18:53,208 --> 00:18:57,333
And no distractions, please.
I'm gonna need you to hide those arms.

234
00:19:01,333 --> 00:19:04,790
So on the night of the accident,
we were only a few miles from Westview.

235
00:19:04,791 --> 00:19:07,749
{\an8}At the exact moment we crashed,
that anomaly was collapsing.

236
00:19:07,750 --> 00:19:10,416
That big, red dome thing in the sky.

237
00:19:11,041 --> 00:19:12,040
Exactly.

238
00:19:12,041 --> 00:19:15,333
I thought that turned out to be some
Avengers training exercise gone wrong.

239
00:19:16,500 --> 00:19:18,416
You're so adorably trusting.

240
00:19:21,041 --> 00:19:23,415
<i>For those of you
who are a little more adventurous,</i>

241
00:19:23,416 --> 00:19:25,790
<i>- you can melt the probiotic candles.</i>
- What?

242
00:19:25,791 --> 00:19:26,874
Look at her skin.

243
00:19:26,875 --> 00:19:29,165
That level of flawless should be illegal.

244
00:19:29,166 --> 00:19:31,125
<i>...face mask. It's completely safe.</i>

245
00:19:31,750 --> 00:19:32,957
